The Prague Stock Exchange falls to a minus against closing of business.
After the steep drop in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
The transactions with the shares of <0xC4><0x8C>EZ reached almost half of the normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange began trading on Tuesday with the collapse on Monday, when it dropped by another six percentage points.
This time it was the reason for the break-in on Wall Street.
Also in the Czech Republic, the market’s reaction to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which it had refused to support a stabilization plan for the financial sector there, is evident.
Fall of shares in Asia
Stocks on the stock exchanges in Asia experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
The index of the Hang Seng stock exchange in Hong Kong lost almost four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was later able to compensate for some of the losses, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while markets were closed in Shanghai.
The stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent after the index there.
"The timing of the rescue operation in the US is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide," Hong Kong Monetary Authority chief Joseph Yam said in a statement.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
U.S. legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass the draft support for the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries could also be affected by the collapse.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to $700 billion (almost 12 trillion K<0xC4><0x8D>) was to be spent.
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush’s request to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would regulate the underlying causes of the financial crisis, thus helping to stabilize the entire economy.
The U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the largest decline in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by nearly seven percent, a similar decline he had most recently seen in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there were hardly any signs that the draft would not pass in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress Makes Concession: U.S. Government May Pump $700 Billion into Banks
The top representatives of the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance for the American financial system.
The vote is scheduled for early next week.
American lawmakers reached a breakthrough in talks on the adoption of a $700 billion bailout plan for the American financial system.
However, this does not mean a victory.
Congressmen have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the U.S. Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
According to various reports, the plan could probably be voted on by Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, an announcement that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor for a revival of financial markets.
After that, however, there will be a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms that could be used to help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package should look like to stabilize the market," said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
According to her, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Legislators met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsold mortgage assets from the financial companies, plunging the financial companies into serious losses and endangering the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of reaching a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
You have to continue the recovery plan, but I think we're on target," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
This is to reassure investors of business in Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision by Congress could affect business on Monday.
However, it is not yet quite clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and it is also unclear whether the negotiations at the last minute could still fail due to a problem.
Legislators hope it will be adopted in the next few days.
But the law will see some changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion should be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
Congress can, however, block the disbursement of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program is not performing its function, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush says progress in negotiations is positive
Although the president has a veto on this decision, Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has persisted, which was based on obtaining finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
President Bush was also pleased with the progress made.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "appreciates the bilateral effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Restriction of golden parachutes
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said the legislators had agreed on responsibility for the money program, taxpayer protection from losses, the conclusion of benefits, and a schedule for financing the plan.
The new law also aims to restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the program and sets up a committee that will be responsible for overseeing the fund.
This is to be led by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard and made a great progress towards a deal that works and is important to the market and to all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who have problems repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages that it buys up, with the goal being to lower the monthly costs for the debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“And that’s because you don’t know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are purchased.
That will be crucial to how the financial sector and the government divide the losses among themselves," Marek told iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week is not decisive in Marek’s view.
"It is much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and adopt it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement for a farewell is the most important thing at this moment," said Marek.
Duel on knife cutting edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can still make calls.
So, of course, it looks like it’s better to just buy a phone.
Nevertheless, there are plenty of reasons why you should buy a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
Surely you hardly buy yourself a great expensive turntable at home to listen to the latest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
Once, such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
This is also the case with music on the go, i.e. with compressed music, in a simplified way - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a player, but just as a Pink Floyd fan will hardly be able to handle headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can play a lot more than just music, but what mobile phones can do, they don’t even create in hints.
No modern device can be used as universally as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, calling and simsing, it can play music and videos, record both, it has a better, sometimes a worse camera and maybe can also navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph.
However, the universality of mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to recharge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, Music Players (especially the simplest) are significantly more powerful.
That’s why you should expect the cheap phones to be able to play no more than a few hours of music.
If you are still on the phone from time to time, you prefer to buy a charger for the office - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the less good ones will last at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation with one time charging off.
There is another problem when you want to overplay the music on your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB port, and not every phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can play the music directly on a storage medium, but only a few card readers can cope with the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With players, you don’t need any special software, except for the iPod.
You only need to feed the device with music from your PC via USB port.
Most mobile phones and players create their own music library, arranged by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the user rating.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address directory, similar to the Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire in particular about the life of the battery, the storage capacity, the quality and the type of sound and, of course, also the ease of use.
If music is primarily a backdrop for you and you only hear it every day for a short time, for example on the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Which almost every cell phone can do.
You also don’t have to control which music formats a phone or player can process.
MP3 creates all, and most of the music you get will just be in this format.
The format is one of the most common, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online.
All you have to do is access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile Internet, and you can already purchase a song or album.
This service in and of itself can be a striking argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is usually limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of music sales (be it via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their phones with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab the phone in the jacket pocket while the player is forgotten at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least one wireless hands-free device with you.
If not, you can access the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns, you’ll get a decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most people will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically mature phones with a 3.5mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players, in turn, lies in the ease of operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) - players can really serve anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the previously normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable, is obvious.
There is no threat of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequent horrifying bill for data transmissions.
Which device should you use now?
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But be careful.
In the basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are usually supported.
Only the most expensive can read 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, then go to Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max 2 GB), you will not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Being among the more sophisticated listeners, prefer to take specialized phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have standalone control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
The most distant is Sony Ericsson, whose phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours) provide you with MP3 players from the above mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't wait long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the European Commission’s final steps in the area of roaming charges regulation, it is so likely to be a paradoxical situation – for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to reproach the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák often agrees, who in the past had often said that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
However, there is another option – a virtual provider.
Particularly the entry of virtual providers into the mobile telephony market brought with it a significant price reduction, which the classical mobile telephony providers had to react to.
Even before companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
It doesn’t take long to look for examples.
In February this year we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in attracting more than 100 thousand customers and thus becoming the country’s fifth largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
They do not require relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-clinic target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and they can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could also take root in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>’s press spokesman also doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment where most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators say chanceless
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries of our region," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, press spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has long been demonstrated by the Group GTS Novera, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, the press spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telefónica O2 in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile’s press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová rarely agrees with O2’s statement: “So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further.”
And she adds: “On T-Mobile’s network, hardly any virtual provider will emerge by the end of the year.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in such a short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
From the customer’s point of view, this is precisely what we consider to be the best.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The action of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the vendors can pull at one strand when it comes to something, also proves the long back and forth about the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was from the company T-Mobile at the time of U:fon’s launch.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
Now, however, U:fon is just an argument as to why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
In view of this approach of the mobile operators, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem to its very typical attitude.
“The entry into the market of a virtual mobile operator would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential prospects was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classical providers," said in his answer to our question Kristián Chalupa from the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS's external relations department.
From representatives of the providers would not surprise such a formulation.
This is more than questionable by an authority that represents the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensures that no one abuses their position in the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile phone services."
Probably, however, pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is really shocking in this case is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same gasoline price at the gas stations is certainly only coincidence and the result of a fierce competition.
"The Authority has not detected any indications of anti-competitive action in this matter, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their trading in the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are also likely to be lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators holds a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for a virtual provider to enter the market, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act failed to enforce the extension of the competences of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know that too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when nobody's looking
Regardless of the functioning of some pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only go to the selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer ordering a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"Should there be cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to a termination of cooperation with the relevant society," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not talk around among the responsible persons of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
The profits from the activities of these companies are not negligible and, in contrast to the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows for such types of speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full access to it like the normal customers of the mobile operators."
That alone, however, should at least seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If the mobile operators close their eyes before such a procedure, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competencies to detect such activities and, if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the suppliers’ declaration that they know nothing about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As the text has already stressed several times, the entry of virtual providers into the market has resulted in a significant fall in the price of the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classical providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - a too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, regulators intervened at these moments, who by no means sought to safeguard the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competences is more than favorable in these cases.
But let’s not throw the gun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon emerges, the Czech mobile market may soon be back in motion.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) further prospects.
And the Czechs will not finally make more expensive phone calls than the rest of Europe.
