The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans asked for the allocation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This is evident from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans should have turned to the US president in 1945.
This can be seen from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengaus" - which was taken on the basis of the Munich agreement by Hitler - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units are not entering German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," a letter signed with the words "people whose destiny is at the heart of the Sudeten".
Since the accession to Czechoslovakia makes the Sudeten Germans - aware of the Czech national character - suspect that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the patronage of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We can't believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million residents, you are allowing this territory to a foreign state that is trying to suppress and eliminate minorities and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of revenge desires of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US President had doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest Gaul on whether the inhabitants would become part of the United States or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat na<0xC3><0xAF>ve in today’s knowledge of post-war history, in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses, it paints a good picture with regard to the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Although the Bohemian Germans had to at least guess that they would negotiate their deportation from the Republic, few of them agreed to such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Still others believed they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was used in the war as a Budweiser German in the navy on the Baltic Sea.
When, at the end of the war, he was taken into British captivity and taken to a prisoner of war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would suit them," Chalupa said.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected him to be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> decrees.
