Even rats have feelings.
A rat or a scabbard flees in danger, does that mean that it also feels fear?
The neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
How can you tell if they feel the same way when they behave the same way we do?
The Internet magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions by famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this to date where we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we should at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and tackle issues of sensation or consciousness in general, we enter rugged terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, she does the same thing as many other animals: she stands dead, fleeing or attacking.
Humans behave in a similar way, leading some scientists to conclude a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe in that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in the execution / control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the rest of the primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So, at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic characteristic may lie in the linguistic nature of man: Since such a large part of his experience is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly affect it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my statements relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness besides it that should be more scientifically accessible.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and that is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But in this approach, followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, one focuses more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I trace them back to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies working memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
In connection with the linguistic nature, there are fine gradations of sensation, because with the help of words and grammar, we can differentiate and categorize states, in order to attribute them to others alongside ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio suggests that sensations from more primitive activities in the body sensation regions of the cortex and brain stem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-genre sensations.
Theoretically, I cannot disagree with this, but I think it is unproven.
Pankseep argues that what appears like fear in rats and humans probably feels the same way in both cases: But how can you check if rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A scabbard flees in danger if she too feels fear?
In my view, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, on the other hand, they do not even scrape a brain.
But is the brainstem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it to humans, how would you prove it to rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even scabies (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove that.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress here on the neural level, if you measure the same in rats and humans.
As I do not study language and consciousness in rats, nor do I study sensations, I do not know if they exist.
