Jeremiah Moss, who runs the blog called "Jeremiah's disappearing New York" (subtitled "The Book of Lamentations: A bitter nostalgic look at the extinct city"), has published part of the city story conversation about Extra Place, which had appeared in the magazine "The New Yorker" in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote at the time: "Extra Place is a small narrow cul-de-sac that remains dark even during the day and is characterized by rusted metal doors of warehouses, closed windows, and rain gutters flying past week-old newspapers".
With a few exceptions, the street looked just like that recently on one evening.
A rat ran through the back of the street, not far from the door that used to lead to the CBGB, where today there is a more expensive clothing store.
Graffiti were seen on the walls and an empty beer bottle lay on the floor not far from a fresh bundle of discarded newspapers.
Some passersby said they had rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested that the road could be polished up a little.
Fields, added that in his opinion, some people underestimate the charm of the street in its current state.
The best years of my life, he said, were in places that were dark, damp, and disgusting.
Bilingual education debate: education in an English-language environment
In this issue of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of the candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior researcher in Caliphonic Studies and senior director in the Department of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice".
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the likelihood of African-American and Hispanic students successfully completing school is lower than that of white students” – which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those who first learn English.
Still, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Let’s take “Sixth Street Prep,” a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently been in the country, are learning English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, astonishing 100 percent fourth grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth year of school were rated well in the English exam.
This astonishing success was achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School places its emphasis on review and practice, on steady control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practises the approach according to which the education is conducted in an English-speaking environment. That is precisely the point that Obama should take into account, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialist teaching.
Mrs. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico. 12 months later, one would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize him.
"It works," she remarked, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like the “Sixth Street Prep” as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The achievements of the school would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within its own party (the national Bildunsvereinigungen have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While he agrees with the point that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the legislation targeting “English only.”
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close the gap in performance, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than despise and trivialize them.
Oil prices fall as a result of renewed fears about the economy
The oil price has fallen sharply on Monday due to fears that even the American bailout plan for the financial markets might not be enough to revive the economy.
Crude futures transactions on the New York Stock Exchange fell by 7 percent to $99.80 per barrel in the morning session.
Since last Monday, the price has dropped by more than $20.
Over the past two weeks, goods markets have been shaken by both Wall Street financial turmoil and strong cyclones in the Gulf of Mexico.
After peaking at $145.29 per barrel in July, prices have fallen to nearly $90 per barrel this month, before rising again as a result of the enormous uncertainty in the financial markets.
On Monday, investors once again expressed concern, although congressmen had announced that they had agreed on a rescue plan this weekend that should be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis is far from over.
In the last chapter of the growing crisis, according to a government announcement on Monday, Citigroup is to buy up the banking operations of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalised the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a rescue plan, it seems unable to revive the mood in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, it is to be expected that demand for goods, including oil, will continue to decline.
Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a statement to investors that forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates had become extremely uncertain.
We believe, they continue to write, that the goods markets will also be affected.
"From the perspective of goods markets, we are most concerned about whether the US virus is spreading globally, especially to China."
The Bank’s analysts have revised their oil consumption expectations downwards due to weak economic growth for the coming year, and their oil and gas price projections for 2009 have been reduced by 20%.
