Rested Gebrselassie breaks its world record
Haile Gebrselassie from Ethiopia has once again shown why some consider him to be the best long-distance runner of all time after breaking his own record in the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to make the 42.2 kilometers in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the win on the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous score of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has thus set his 26th world record in his versatile career, in which he has achieved at least one World Championship title or set a world record on every track from one kilometre to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon out of fear, perhaps exaggerated in retrospect, that air pollution could worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions - in the sun and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie has won at an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya switched to long-distance, the record time for marathon in the last 10 years has fallen by more than 2 minutes, since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won in Berlin in 1998 with the result 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and was therefore unable to train for a week.
Obviously, he was refreshed after a break and did not return rusted.
“I’m so happy,” he told reporters.
"Everything went perfectly.
I started training again a week ago and had some concerns today, but in the end everything was great."
He was criticized – especially in Kenya, Ethiopia’s rivals from East Africa – for over-orchestrating his races, avoiding many of the world’s best marathon stars in general, relying too much on the race leaders as if it were a track race, and setting world records over the competition.
But this criticism hardly harms the size of Gebrselassies as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the centre of the track in 1:02:04.
Two elite runners from Kenya, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi have continued to challenge Gebrselassie after the pacemakers had slowed down.
Just over three miles before the finish, Gebrselassie made his last run to separate from Kwambai, who came second in 2:05:36, improving his best time by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
For women, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now German, has completed a remarkable year by showing the seventh fastest result of all time at 2:19:19.
The world record of 2:15:25 holds Paul Radcliff from Great Britain.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko had surprisingly won the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the games in Beijing due to problems described as a back injury, but has recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She skilfully planned her run by having a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners torn out first, but outpaced after 30 kilometers.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop from Kenya came third in 2:25:01.
The pride and hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles from the sparkling, noisy and gigantic bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first entirely black town in the country and hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she describes – and which made her a tourist destination by taking her into the Florida Travel Guide, produced by the Federal Writers Project at the time of the Depression – is and remains a place of a very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, prosperous and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t know what’s missing.”
Even nowadays, in a year in which a black presidential candidacy, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open talk on racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very keen on how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and parish member of the city's oldest church.
It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the country’s average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the – sometimes condemned, sometimes praised – black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And really, the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in idiom, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Freaking like Oskar in real life as well as in literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and whatever fits classrooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added: "Some people didn't like this."
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric woman who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came to the city brewing, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today imagines something on her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were intrigued, while many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he swinged in his chair, on a rear-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, in which Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporaneous Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville, there was no big commemoration, no public readings in a big way.
"I don't think they understood their contribution in the world or their legacy in the least," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
“At this time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away,” Mr. Franklin said.
“There was even a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to enforce integration by calling its decision in Brown's case against the school council "offensive rather than respecting my race."
Residents today say that although the elimination of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - they hugged their teacher in the morning and they hugged their teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be sustained for so long, she added, until teachers and students were no longer coming from the same place.
"You didn't embrace his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," said Ms. Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped create room for more of Zora Neale Hurston’s—black writers, actors, and artists who overcame prejudice, as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a highly praised Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, and once again made it a part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway enlivened the city, accelerated the whole thing at peak speed, aroused real citizen pride," Ms Nathiri said.
Ms. Boyd put it a little simpler: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city’s self-image.
There were more and more crowds, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-appreciate the past.
Eatonville was included in the National Historic Register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays, Eatonville is still a special place in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, prior approval is necessary and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in field work - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a brave, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that her shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew larger, an increased degree of home pride was also born.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with all her problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who intends to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city council or the police, which he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said on a Sunday after church.
"But if you actually stop and look at your story for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
Here in New York we speak fluent financial latin.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan kept away from the newspaper stands and the huge TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t even realize they’re in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass facades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York, have the worst horror working day every day since the stock market collapse of 1929.
The suppliers still push the metal tea trolleys along sidewalks with loud claps and carry trays loaded with muffins for breakfast sessions.
Latinos still roamed between apartments as human pack animals loaded with around 50 ironed t-shirts hanging from a yoke-like pole lying on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for their breakfast bags at food stands on the sidewalks and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4 and 7 pm.
It didn’t feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon, because of all the doomsday talk, I decided to open a new savings account.
Although I had decided to lay down my duty on the quiet late afternoon in my JP Morgan Chase branch, about 20 people were already queuing.
Not at the cash desks to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists about the way to Macy’s department store and where new customers open accounts.
Most of the people before me, I learned later from Starr, my "personal banker licensed" for the same reason that I was in line.
Unlike me, however, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks, in places from which they commuted, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (a little like a building savings bank), cooperative banks, and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state and say they treat their customers like family.
Last year, 15 of these banks went silently and quietly bankrupt.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went over bankruptcy management and when last Friday New Yorker drove home over the weekend, Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion in savings, was looking for a savings buyer.
Fearful of another collapse, the office and store employees who were in front of me brought their cash to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank responsible for most of the rescue purchases on Wall Street.
Quite ordinary New Yorkers have been acquiring a fluent financial latin in the last few weeks.
A woman who was on the phone in my Chinese tribal supermarket referred with so much familiarity to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and their skinny-looking CEO, Dick Fuld, as if she were taunting a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, who's around the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment block, has gotten away from our usual conversational themes about Brad and Angelina and my grocery delivery.
