Travel ban for Gary Glitter
Gary Glitter, the glam rock star who has been convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned from travelling to France and Spain.
Judges imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities controlling him that he wanted to travel to Spain via France.
Police in Kent were granted a travel ban last Thursday after providing judges with evidence of Glitter’s criminal records for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the Ashford District Court hearing in Kent, but was represented by the law firm Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the Court reported: "On Thursday, September 25, the Kent police at Ashford County Court requested permission to prevent Mr. Paul Glad's foreign travel to France and Spain by March 25.
Paul Gadd was not personally present."
As required by the sex offender register, Glitter, 64, had informed the authorities that he wanted to travel abroad.
He must inform the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He must also notify the police 7 days before his scheduled departure.
Failure to notify the authorities could result in a prison sentence of 5 years.
Police in Kent said they would not discuss individual cases or Glitter's possible whereabouts in the country.
A spokeswoman for Kent's police unit said: "The Kent police will do everything necessary to protect children in this country and abroad."
"We believe it is easier to control someone who is in the UK because we have a comprehensive system to effectively prevent any potential risks."
"It is the top concern of the police in Kent to protect the residents of Kent and we are working closely together to monitor the behavior of registered sex offenders in the country to minimize any risk that might exist for the population.
