Conversation - From the Blood That Became Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Donation Service were infected with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at clarifying the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and drawing up guidelines to prevent another disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee at the time, whose goal was to develop a new system for managing blood cans in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started its work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood-conserving system in Quebec,” recalls Dr Décary.
The situation was daunting.
“Through enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood canned food and through work in this field over the following years, we have regained public trust,” she says, before emphasizing proudly that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec’s population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted according to the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of cattle insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
“And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which states that exclusion measures are applied when one does not know this and when a disease progresses only slowly, as is apparently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was accepted from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proven that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has quite a sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation period that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, you would have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV being transmitted via a blood can.
I believe that these days you can feel comfortable getting a blood transfusion or prescribing it to restore health," says the head of Hema-Quebec.
<0x60>Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We must monitor continuously," Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate care in addition to safe care.
“The demand is increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which, on average, includes only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
With these 3%, we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to hold them and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” Francine Décary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood preserves, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, which used to be considered biomedical waste, there is blood rich in stem cells, which can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to take off more than a thousand a year.
“We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year,” continues Dr. Décary, who describes this program of cord blood removal as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it,” because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
