Free Speech - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director General of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world’s largest gold mining company sought a defamation lawsuit of over six million against three authors and a small mediocre publishing house, with the aim of opening a “public transparent debate.”
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of slander charges, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to hold a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposing opinions.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defenses and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is, by the way, often to ruin the defenders in order to enforce a consensual settlement that silences the opposing side and, moreover, deters anyone who dares to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things before public opinion.
Contrary to what is commonplace in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually carried out through the exchange of ideas and not through battering.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had exposed its books and files and opened a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent testing teams that could have brought light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and sweeps the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada aside with a gesture of the hand.
Could Mr Garver explain how he can at the same time ask for a "public" debate and yet disregard the opinions of that public?
Apparently, in the world of the vice-president, this word covers only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada is doing so mainly because they reject the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is ready to listen and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the ‘public debate’, Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, demanding them to stop using that term...).
Aside from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth-finding that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss topics that the wealthy companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, she does not want a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit this kind of unjustified lawsuit.
