The Psychology of Excess Bidding - or Why We're Ready to Pay More
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the error bid.
New York University neurologists and economic scientists have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people don't want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have attempted to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play the lottery, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the subjects' active brain regions were examined by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cortex of the brain, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent's overbiding plays a major role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the “self-reward” of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believed that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally conducted studies to track the money.
In this case, three groups should bid against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their deployments.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged as winners.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to take higher stakes than those in the control or "profit" group.
"These findings are not derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far justified the behaviour observed in auctions only with the joy of winning or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are being treated, because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travelers are recommended to be vaccinated against the viruses A and B in any case, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after consuming the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Every year around 1 million people worldwide die from hepatitis B, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people are undergoing drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to see the general practitioner at the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, organised for the first time by patient representatives worldwide in 2004.
