Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method for developing new technologies for accident prevention if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was unveiled that inspired Nissan engineers to create new accident avoidance systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the auto-robot-controlled biomimetic system BR23C, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval “private area” very similar to our own “shield,” said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers adopted the idea of the laser-controlled rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180 degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is detected in fractions of a second, and the auto-robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by rotating the tires at the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it weren’t so, the auto-robot wouldn’t be able to react fast enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto-robot project.
The system must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they dodge other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, dodging can not be done up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the maneuverability of the tires.
While there are endless possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers could only use the auto-robot to rotate, or to accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and react to them accordingly.
It does not need to store it, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so that it only uses a handful of KB memory on a continuous basis.
It does not require gigabytes and megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production in the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately guiding the driver around obstacles and thus guiding him to his destination.
