Despite the election debacle, no heads are still rolling, and the staff debates have been postponed at the head of the Bavarian CSU.
Party leader Erwin Huber and Prime Minister Beckstein still remain in their offices, the question is just how long this grace lasts.
The fate of the tandem after the disastrous 17% vote loss will be decided on the last weekend of October at the Extraordinary Party Congress.
But the much slandered duo already made it clear that it does not want to stick on their armchairs.
They want to appease the angry faction and the party base, which one day after the "Bayern tsunami" demanded personal consequences in the face of the loss of the absolute majority.
Five years ago – admittedly, under the leadership of Edmund Stoiber, who is at the height of his career – the Christian Social Union still reached 60.7 percent, but now, a year after the coup against Stoiber, they were only able to secure 43.4 percent of the vote.
For 46 years, the CSU was the "alone government" in Bavaria, which generates 18 percent of German GDP.
Although the Conservatives remain the determining force in the southern state, which is also important for the Hungarian economy, they will in future have to rule in a coalition.
As a first sign of the internal restructuring of the party, the potential successor of Huber, vice-president and Federal Agriculture Minister Horst Seehofer will also be involved in the exploration team, which is conducting exploratory talks with the liberal FDP, or the right-wing "free voters" about a possible Munich coalition.
An irony of fate is that with the list of "free voters" Gabriele Pauli enters the legislature, whose anti-stolen behavior the Huber-Beckstein duo first exploited, then mercilessly serve the determined politician.
The CSU leadership is now concentrating all its forces on the stabilization of Beckstein.
In this transition process, Stoiber, who has hitherto pulled the threads out of the background, will play an active role. The former prime minister and CSU chairman called September 28 the "bitterest day of his political career".
On Monday, Huber made a few toxic remarks towards the CDU - in his opinion, the CSU deserved far more support from the sister party.
Other CSU politicians interpreted the defeat as a signal to the CDU and thus also to Angela Merkel.
If the CSU, which also contributed a lot to national success in 2005, is not put back on its feet with a joint force act, Merkel can not again become Chancellor after the Bundestag elections in September 2009.
Merkel, who has made no mistake about her disappointment with the fiasco, believes that the CSU’s loss of terrain will not have a negative impact on the big coalition in Berlin.
What is relative, however, is that the wounded CSU will not be easier to govern, and the crisis of the Social Democrats continues.
With 18.6 percent, the SPD achieved its best result so far in Bavaria since 1946.
Lukashenko opposition: 110-0
In the elections on Sunday, no member of the opposition managed to enter the Ukrainian parliament.
Russian observers believe that this is due to prosperity and stability in the country led by Alexander Lukashenko, but the OECD suspects illegalities in the counting of votes.
The OECD, which has sent 450 observers from 43 countries, has not recognised the elections.
The legislature of the 10-million-inhabitant state has been without opposition for decades, yet the opposing party assembled under the name of "United Democratic Forces" (ODS) before yesterday's elections has earnestly hoped that Lukashenko, who in the improper elections and thanks to a constitutional amendment in 2006, would renew his presidential mandate for the fourth time.
That is why the ODS has even distanced itself from the previously planned boycotts.
Ukraine is becoming economically increasingly dependent thanks to the rising prices of natural gas imports from Russia. For the alleviation of the price increases even loans were taken, and the country has also agreed to sell the Beltransgas, the owner of the country-leading gas pipeline, to the Russians. In the background of the expectations of the opposition Lukas was high after the hope that Ukraine would improve its relationship with the EU.
The evaluation report of the OECD elections provided for a temporary relaxation, in which the emphasis was on the positive movements rather than on the shortcomings - such as the exclusion of one third of the opposition candidates from the elections.
However, the OECD’s rapid report on Monday already criticized the campaign – according to which opposition members are not likely to appear in the press – and in particular the fact that the opposition was not allowed to be present when counting the votes.
Despite all this, the opposition is able to see an improvement in the political system: political prisoners have been set free, for example, and Minsk is even prepared for minor confrontations with Moscow by continuing to refuse the recognition of the independence of the renegade Georgian provinces of South Ossetia and Abkhazia, although Russia, with which Ukraine on paper has independently considered a federal state, has made one of the two territories.
"We have taken two steps forward and one backward, but the most important thing is that the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has begun," Milinkevich said.
According to the opposition candidate for the 2006 presidential election, a continuation is desirable, although "the powerful have become afraid to let even one opposition in parliament".
The opposition does not plan to protest against the results, but rather seeks to clarify the need for economic reform to the voters.
"We are struggling with a lot of problems here - the opposition newspapers have to be printed in Russia, the local authorities are putting stones in our way in the distribution, but nevertheless I see that more and more people are supporting change, even the elderly" - Milinkevich said, alluding to the fact that not even the most supported layer of pensioners agree with the Lukashenko regime, whose only social merit is the production.
"Thanks to the country's debt and the increase in the trade deficit, it is only a matter of time before the "social security" that reminds us of the silence of a cemetery begins to crumble," Milinkevich said.
Unlike opposition politicians, Russian observers have described the elections as democratic.
Sergei Lebedev, head of the mission of the Community of Independent States, told the news agency Ria Novosti: "People believe in the deeds, not the words". The absence of opposition is therefore proof of the maturity of Belarusian voters.
Brunetta: “From now on, breakfast will be served before work”
For the first time in the history of Palazzo Chigi, there are rotating doors for officials’ entrances and exits.
From today onwards, the measure will take effect against those scoundrels who first stamp and then go drinking coffee during working hours.
The new "Anti-Lack of Fur Law" was introduced today by Renato Brunetta, Minister of Public Administration, and by Mauro Masi, Secretary-General of the Presidency of the Council of Ministers.
"Revolving doors are a means to increase work efficiency through a higher attendance rate and more services," said Minister Brunetta.
"Now begins a new era of responsibility and transparency.
This is reformism,” Brunetta stresses once again.
The Palazzo Chigi ends in all the buildings of the Presidency of the Council of Ministers.
Masi says: “The choice of rotating doors is also of great symbolic value.”
There was no resistance on the part of the officials, the secretary-general assured: "This process was supported by all, the cooperation came from all sides".
All in all, there is no more breakfast during working hours; end with coffee or croissant.
Brunettas advises with a smile: "A good cappuccino at 7 o'clock works wonders".
During a meeting of the Superior Committee of Public Administration (Scuola Superiore della Pubblica Amministrazione)
From Rome, the minister announced that "within three months the absences of officials have been reduced to 50%, that is, 60,000 more people are present at work per year".
He adds that it is necessary to strengthen the efficiency of the public administration of Italy
"their wage dynamics - according to the minister - have been twice as large as the private sector in the last 8-10 years and far above the inflation rate."
Meanwhile, thousands of officials have joined forces to counter the Brunetta Decree as part of the appeal supported by Codacons.
"While the Minister of Public Service profiles himself with figures about less absenteeism at work - writes the Consumer Centre - the people of 'working lazy furs' are growing continuously.
In fact, thousands of correct and valuable public officials have joined forces to declare war on the unlawful norms of the Decree."
In particular, the Regional Administrative Court (TAR) is fighting for additional financial compensation for work-related illness; so is the planned extension of the mandatory house arrest of the sick worker, during which inspection visits can be made and further aspects of the Minister’s innovations are challenged.
Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day in Italy, 2,500 accidents occur at work, three people die and 27 remain incapacitated for life.
For the year 2007, the data of the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These figures show the severity of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) will celebrate the 58th National Day of the Victims of Work Accidents in all provinces of Italy, in order to draw the attention of social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is," confirmed the President of the Republic Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention at the workplace, to protect the injured workers, to support the families of the victims and to raise awareness of public opinion".
"An outrageous "basta" has risen up after this; understandable in tragedies, which, measured by their magnitude, trigger some whirlwind in the media and public sympathy. But the everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events, which can even repeat themselves in their own dynamics".
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness in school frameworks by young people who feed on the world of work are of particular importance.
It is our duty to draw attention to this phenomenon and not to distract it from its social seriousness.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency, which offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules aimed at ending the problem".
"The data on occupational accidents seem to signal a slight improvement, but this does not exclude that the number of occupational deaths is far too high," said Anmil president Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this 'positive tendency' to mean less attention. That's what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How to believe that you are basically doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents. You can fight it through various actions.
We believe that stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate the workers who are already starting in school.”
"A further effort is necessary - he adds - as far as communication and public opinion awareness is concerned.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that constitutes a social emergency is required".
Mercandelli also addressed the “progressive deterioration in protection for the victims of occupational accidents” and denounced the “abolition of the social system we have been fighting against in recent years.”
"The aim is therefore to return to the worker a guarantee on insurance so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or random donations decided by a legislator from time to time".
Mp3 Player Under Charge: Risk of Hearing Damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which cites the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on Current and Recently Identified Health Risks) of the EU in a report distributed today in Brussels.
“The report makes it clear that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for at least five years a week for more than one hour a day are at risk of permanent hearing loss.”
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people, who usually place portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, will irreparably damage their hearing without knowing it," said Meglena Kuneva.
“The scientific findings – as the EU says – show a clear risk that urges rapid action.
What really matters is to raise awareness among consumers and to make this information a common good.
In view of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the existing control systems to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music devices among young people.
"The scientists - concludes the EU communication - confirm that they are rightly concerned and that the EU Commission, together with the other EU members and those concerned, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music devices and similar devices."
There is already a European standard which limits the level of noise from portable music devices to 100 dB, worrying about the damage that could come from excessive noise pollution.
These damages can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and length of noise exposure.
In its report, the EU’s Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music devices listen to loud music only five hours a week (lower than 89 decibels), so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who exceed this limit risk complete loss of hearing within five years.
This represents 5-10% of the users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
Roma, Alemanno give the start to the "Commission for the Future of the Capital"
We start today, it's supposed to be over in March, in June, the balance is drawn.
This is the procedure laid down by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of the Capital of Rome". The Commission met this morning at the new headquarters behind the Caracalla Thermal Baths.
In six months, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will work out the guidelines for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the city council and the municipal council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present the strategic plan for Rome in June with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and the Mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural opinions are represented in it," - emphasises Alemanno. "It will present proposals for a development plan for Rome, whose political responsibility will remain with the city councils and the municipal councils.
There is no redistribution of responsibilities, only the will to have a place where one can develop a great project for Rome.
Their task will be completed in March and the Commission will disband again, as such a project must have a timely end point.
In June - the mayor announces - we will present the strategic plan in which we will take advantage of the work done by the Commission".
Anyone who calls into question the Commission's competence, since its opinion is lacking in commitment, replies to Alemanno: "Everything depends on the work that the Commission will do and on the quality of its proposals.
If, as in France, the Attali Commission, it delivers quality results – and this will certainly be the case in Rome – then its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often, politics deals with the everyday problems and emergencies that occur from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to have a longer period in view, in order to work seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city in a deeper perspective".
The Mayor of Rome attaches great importance to clarifying the following: "This commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free, it will not cost a cent to the Roman citizens and it will make us think, it will employ the best minds of the capital".
According to Alemanno, "it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetic nor static in order to enable our city to make a quality leap - which it really needs - and thus take a joint step into the future".
A future, according to the Mayor of Rome, which "will not only limit itself to the current municipal boundaries, but will look much further", not only in terms of the role of Rome as a metropolis and political capital of Italy, but also as the future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean."
Obama – the first anti-American president? Here is a statement
A well-known American politician who cares a lot about being regarded as independent wrote: “Barack Obama will be the second anti-American president.
The first was Jimmy Carter, who, through his decisions, decimated the U.S. economy and cultivated relations with the hostile Islam (and still does so today as a private man).
The attacks against Obama are becoming more and more violent, especially now that the elections are approaching.
A lady from Miami wrote on an internet page: "This person is full of ambition.
Obama is very naughty: he thinks he will get the highest office in a nation that has seen a total of two black governors and five black senators!"
Actually, however, these attacks don’t have much to say; they are racist attacks and they don’t answer voters’ question: will he be a good president? And then there are the polls; all say that Obama will win with a big lead.
Also in this case, there are people who speak with the heart and not with the head.
A newspaper from Mississippi, in the deepest south of the United States, wrote in its editorial: Only in the voting booth will we know who the real American patriot will give his voice.
Here comes a mentality of the United States that has been hidden until the last time.
"Tell us what you want, then we'll decide who we're going to make our crows for, whether for Obama or for McCain."
There are people there who swear that if Obama wins, we will emigrate from America.
Something you’ve never heard before – only now, when the success of the black candidate seems so certain.
In any case, despite all these considerations, the final weapon for the Democrats is George Bush.
1,500 people were asked: What mistakes did Bush make during his tenure? 89% answered: the war in Iraq.
America is changing.
The nation lost 50,000 soldiers in Vietnam and was sent home with a kick in the ass.
In Iraq, 4,500 soldiers lost their lives and the Americans were not forced to pack.
For the majority, Iraq remains Bush’s weak point.
The person who will take his place is faced with a huge task.
USA. The financial collapse also leaves its mark on journalists: You can already feel the cuts in the newspapers. And many blame the Internet, the "killer" of the printing press.
Five hundred American journalists were interviewed by the PEW Research Center about their situation and their mental control regarding the future.
Today, almost all journalists are pessimistic about their future.
Nevertheless, they did not really express concern about the general credibility of the information concerning the persons in charge.
They don’t feel as alone as they used to be.
The problem for American journalists is money.
For these journalists, the 2008 crisis is a crisis of an economic model that has been destroyed.
In addition, the major problems are due to the cuts in the newsroom, i.e. the space in which the editors work to compile the newspaper.
It is a problem that needs to be solved – according to the interviewed journalists – if one wants to prevent traditional journalism, as the general public understands it, from shrinking significantly.
A clear but complicated pessimism fills the American journalist today.
Six out of ten journalists and executive seniors of the printing press believe that journalism at the national level is on the wrong track.
In the local area, it is even 65% for executives.
Printed vs. Broadcast.
It is not difficult for journalists to imagine in which direction the web is going.
The most important publishing groups are paving the way for the Internet, which is seen by many as the “killer” of the printing press.
The “economic pressure” experienced by journalists has increased by up to 79%.
The 500 interviewed journalists have admitted to wanting to join the new technology, hoping "they bring something good to journalism."
The biggest rift in American journalism today lies between the editors-in-chief of the newsroom and the reporters who work for it.
56% of national-level editors are confident that their reporters share their values with them, while only 23% are at the local level.
Some think it has to do with “safety at work.”
The company managers, who are afraid of losing their jobs within three years, are 47% at national level.
For journalists, it is 30%.
The topic of "safe work" in the team (our "editor", note) is always a topical topic in the USA.
Only 13% of journalists work under contract.
In a huge nation like the United States, with 300 million inhabitants and thousands of newspapers, magazines, radio and TV stations and internet operators, employers offer as it pleases them and so it becomes a matter of take it or leave it.
The editors-in-chief get very often very high wages, but the editor can sometimes get only 10,000 euros per month, plus pension and insurance money.
As for the holidays, things get complicated: a certain amount of days in the first year, so and so many after the third, finally reaching 15 holiday days after a certain number of years.
But American journalists, as they themselves admit, often become “sick” throughout the year.
It is a matter of climate.
UNIPOL: JUDGMENT IN ROME: DANILO COPPOLA STAYS IN GROTTAFERRATA
The President of the Second Penal Chamber of the Court in Rome, Carmelo Rinaudo, has decided to reject the request of the real estate agent, who had asked to be transferred from Grottaferrata to Rome.
It is being investigated against Coppola for bankruptcy in the context of the investigation into the counter-agreement in the case of the acquisition of Unipol-Bnl.
In the course of the trial against him during the last week, his release from house arrest was converted into a residence obligation in Grottaferrata.
His lawyers Michele Gentiloni and Gaetano Pecorella had asked to allow the real estate agent to be relocated from the provincial city to an apartment in the capital.
According to the court, such transfers (against which the prosecution had spoken out) could give him the opportunity to influence his society and get evidence accusing him.
The elite is in danger.
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion White House savings package: a large portion of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times issue, which reports how the crisis is gradually dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast souls, which has always favored the state institutions and the business community, and those neoconservatives who are hostile to “those in Washington” and the financial world, and especially those in the south and the center of voters.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example just mentioned is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is announcing or even already representing: not only in the United States, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-feared events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to foreign countries and at the same time manage a tremendous amount of wealth from private households living in a single state.
This means an immediate political problem for the governments: namely, how to behave towards the families concerned, which also represent an enormous body of voters.
The crisis thus appears economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have strayed so far and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its splitting into different national and international conflicts, is unable to find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and especially distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the US in the economic situation have to save themselves without outside help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two prerequisites not to be overvalued – under certain circumstances – on which no international organization and no market will otherwise be able to rely in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
It is paradoxically right now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked empire, a realm of ever differentiated technologies, of the intangible, that we must suddenly see how our future will depend more and more on the essentially material things: water, harvest and oil.
Although they can all be transported from one place to another in the world, they are nevertheless linked to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Hence, the person who has such a territory is at an advantage over another who lives in an area without yields, waterless or free from oil reserves.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a brief introduction.
Whoever says territories, governments, politics says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to manage things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of inappropriateness, a sense of distantness, all directed at a whole class of managers of the Western countries.
It seems to be clearing the way for large sections of the population to believe that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content appears to the majority as ever more foreign and outgoing.
The demand for leadership thus feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of the de-empowerment of the leading class and of the traditional political establishment. This is manifested in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the immediate shift of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the right-wing Labour-Party plays over the collapse in Austria and Bavaria.
You get the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value regarding what is going on today in the lower social strata of the West and is being amplified by the financial crisis and driven to overdimensionality.
In the face of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a “rebellion of the masses.”
Keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that raises up on walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and to be able to climb up walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centers, one of which has now seemingly almost reached its goal.
With an adhesive applied on an area of only 2.5 sq cm, the researchers succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of adhesive can be imagined as a series of spaghetti-arranged tubes," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered in microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
Tests conducted with various materials, such as glass teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than reptiles’ foot holding ability, while at the same time “removing it from the wall without any problems,” said Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton’s Faculty of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe it is, but the researchers are thinking of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could fall within the field of spaceflight.
So for now, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER ART OF RESEARCH – also the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the California scientists present an adhesive made of microfiber that cleans itself from dust like hair by moving on a surface and thus always maintains a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, especially in summer, can cause serious harm to health if they are taken at the same time as certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, has repeatedly pointed out the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with drug intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he once again sounded the alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines to such an extent that they are virtually reduced to health.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
DRUGS IN DANGER – The same drug agency had warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mixture in a report two years ago, stressing to be careful what is being drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepan or methadone.
It’s not just grapefruit – according to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, the director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually immediately passed on to the various international manufacturers, who are so free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there is still some uncertainty, do not be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor," the expert of the Ansa agency emphasizes.
The Nobel Prize in Economics goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the establishment of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neokeynesian who teaches at the University of Princeton and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 11, 2001 attacks, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times editorial that this second event was more decisive for U.S. history than the assassinations.
A prediction that received not little polemic as an answer and was presented to the economist years later, but today proves to be completely correct.
"I am surprised and shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals in the context of the collapses of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from the public eye," Krugman said in a statement at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value," but also a banaliser with a "very aggressive style, particularly directed against the Bush administration's excessive liberalism."
Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package is released
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, among freelancers and in the public administration, as a free replacement for Microsoft’s Office.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, which is supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself with some new features to the public: in addition to a revised and now more spartan designed start menu, a completely guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x is now finally achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard IS.
Eight against was also on the compatibility with Microsoft Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which facilitates e.g. sending via email. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules while preserving the original appearance of the page.
Thus, "hybrid" PDF files can now also be generated, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited with multiple hands by different users, thus avoiding conflicts with changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a Frabe to guarantee a better correction process.
Some companies are about to publish various features of OpenOffice on the web (on the cloud), while the final result is to be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus, it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
Upon request, you can have the installation CD sent to your home or office.
However, while free of charge can be an incentive for the distribution of the program in private households, it is also especially in the area of business where OpenOffice could succeed: after all, various public administration institutions and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means an optimal help for small and medium-sized businesses, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word-related text creation program; Calc, the spreadsheet program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, for creating presentations like with PowerPoint; Dbase for running databases instead of the more familiar Access; and finally Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can easily be exceeded at already 3 million and 600 thousand.
