Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This picture by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-saal complexes in the periphery, means death in the long run for the single-saal cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the traits of a cultural crime.
It’s like losing a friend with whom you’ve travelled a stretch of road full of emotions,” says the director of the film “Nuovo Cinema Paradiso,” which 20 years ago brought him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes. It’s the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a probably lost cinema world forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the last five years, the tremendous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these mints paid for most of the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This indicates that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but the main thing is to preserve the already existing, because closing a hall in the city, not all of its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not comply with existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be necessary".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, due to fears about the old cinemas, decided to protect them by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historic center and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax advantages for the cinema operators as well as benefits for the public regarding local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-restricted areas of the center and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a pleasing initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also develop new concepts.
Certainly, however, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to align with the superpower of the multiplex halls, because after all, the audience today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid seeing the dust-covered posters.
