When the energy emanates from the waves, the big ones suddenly come up
It is an unfathomable source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface, and it is only now that this seems to be understood by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been being considered and studied for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now the environmental organizations and the rising oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to double the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
There are also the currents and tides.
Giants on attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy is Enersis, which in 2005 signed a contract to build a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies in the traditional energy sector are relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said a spokesperson for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering the possibility of working with us.”
It is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that especially in Alaska, oil continues to be extracted by the U.S. and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers say there is growing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still under development, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of rather small dimensions and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the float via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn drives a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipes.
So far, there are four planned plants of this type, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using subsea turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator due to the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, a particular interest immediately deserves the potential that lies in the tides.
Although this is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, sunlight and also waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of current.
The tidal energy in particular is what led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest as much as $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
